				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Double posting, but the story continues..
<br />
<br />CPLD start-up should be safe, due to the NES CPU reset having a delay.  But since reset is done by the lockout chip and by charging a capacitor, how different is a toploader and famicom?  I don't know.  But definitely they should have delays built in, as I realize now it would be stupid anyways if the CPU started as soon as possible (possibly before the memory is ready, etc).
<br />
<br />I've got the reset detector figured out, it's as simple as using a capacitor charged by the M2 clock to release it from reset mode.  Though I'm getting kind of stingy with the I/Os at this point (I think the reset could share an I/O with part of the i2c if it has to, as I don't think one wouldn't ever need both at the same time).</div>

